Russian Diplomats Visit Ponghwa-ri 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 23 (KCNA) -- Russian Ambassador Andrei Karlov and staff members of the Russian embassy here visited the Ponghwa-ri Revolutionary Museum on Tuesday on the occasion of the 56th anniversary of the signing of the agreement on economic and cultural cooperation between the DPRK and the Russian Federation.
 The guests laid bouquets before the statue of Kim Hyong Jik, who was an outstanding leader of the anti-Japanese national liberation movement in Korea, and paid tribute to him. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Then, they looked round materials and relics on display at the museum, being briefed on the fact that Kim Hyong Jik set out a noble idea of "Jiwon" at his early age, formed the Korean National Association to materialize it and dedicated all his life to the struggle for the independence of the country and national liberation through his energetic revolutionary activities. 
 At the end of the visit the ambassador said that Kim Hyong Jik devoted his all to the struggle to liberate the country from the yoke of the Japanese imperialists, adding that President Kim Il Sung inherited his noble spirit and brought national liberation to the Korean people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He wished the Korean people would achieve a great success under the wise leadership of Kim Jong Il this year marking the 60th anniversary of national liberation.

Premier Pak Pong Ju Arrives in Beijing 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beijing, March 22 (KCNA Correspondent) -- Premier of the DPRK Cabinet Pak Pong Ju arrived in Beijing Tuesday morning by special plane to pay an official goodwill visit to the People's Republic of China.
 He was accompanied by Vice-Premier Ro Tu Chol, Chairman of the State Planning Commission Kim Kwang Rin, Minister of Foreign Trade Rim Kyong Man, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Kim Hyong Jun, Vice-Minister of Agriculture Kim Hyok Jin, Vice-Minister of Chemical Industry Han Sung Jun and other suite members. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The premier and his party were greeted at the airport by Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs of China Wu Dawei, Chinese Ambassador to the DPRK Wu Donghe and officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Ambassador Choe Jin Su and staff members of the DPRK embassy in Beijing were on hand. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A Chinese woman and a woman from the DPRK embassy presented bouquets to Pak Pong Ju. 
 A welcome ceremony took place at the Great Hall of the People Tuesday afternoon. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present at the ceremony together with Pak Pong Ju were Vice-Premier Ro Tu Chol, Chairman of the State Planning Commission Kim Kwang Rin, Minister of Foreign Trade Rim Kyong Man, DPRK Ambassador to China Choe Jin Su, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Kim Hyong Jun, Vice-Minister of Agriculture Kim Hyok Jin, Vice-Minister of Chemical Industry Han Sung Jun and other suite members. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Staff members of the DPRK embassy in Beijing were on hand. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Also present at the ceremony were Premier of the State Council of China Wen Jiabao, Vice-Chairman of the Central Committee of the Jiusan Society Hong Fazeng, Minister of Foreign Affairs Li Zhaoxing, Director of the State Environment Protection Administration Xie Zhenhua, Chinese Ambassador to the DPRK Wu Donghe, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Wu Dawei, Vice-Minister of Commerce Wei Jianquo and officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Pak Pong Ju in company with Wen Jiabao reviewed a guard of honor of the three services of the Chinese People's Liberation Army.

Talks between DPRK and Chinese Premiers Held 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beijing, March 22 (KCNA Correspondent) -- Talks between Premier of the DPRK Cabinet Pak Pong Ju and Premier of the State Council of China Wen Jiabao were held at the Great Hall of the People Tuesday afternoon.
 At the talks both sides informed each other of the situation in their countries and exchanged views on boosting the bilateral relations of friendship and cooperation and on a series of issues of mutual concern. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK side highly appreciated the positive efforts made by the new collective leadership of China with Hu Jintao as general secretary to consolidate and develop the DPRK-China friendship provided by the leaders of the elder generation of the two countries and reiterated the stand of the Workers' Party of Korea and the DPRK government to boost these friendly relations together with the Chinese comrades. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK side referred to the fact that the Korean army and people, united close around leader Kim Jong Il, are bringing about a great revolutionary surge in socialist construction thanks to the Songun policy and the might of the single-minded unity. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Chinese side said that the Sino-DPRK friendship is growing stronger under the concern of the top leaders of the two countries, adding that these relations are an important part of the external relations of the Chinese party and government and it is of realistic significance to protect and develop the ties under the complicated situation.
 The Chinese side stressed that it is in the common interests of the two peoples to develop the economic cooperation between the two countries. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It noted it is pleased with the successes made by the Korean people in various fields under the wise leadership of Kim Jong Il and wished them greater success in the socialist construction. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The talks proceeded in a sincere and friendly atmosphere. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present at the talks from the DPRK side were Vice-Premier Ro Tu Chol, Chairman of the State Planning Commission Kim Kwang Rin, Minister of Foreign Trade Rim Kyong Man, DPRK Ambassador to China Choe Jin Su, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Kim Hyong Jun, Vice-Minister of Agriculture Kim Hyok Jin, Vice-Minister of Chemical Industry Han Sung Jun and other suite members. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present from the Chinese side were Minister of Foreign Affairs Li Zhaoxing, Director of the State Environment Protection Administration Xie Zhenhua, Chinese Ambassador to the DPRK Wu Donghe, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Wu Dawei, Vice-Minister of Commerce Wei Jianquo and officials concerned.

Japan Urged to Stop Distortion of History 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, March 23 (KCNA) -- A spokesman for the Central Committee of the Educational and Cultural Workers' Trade Union of Korea issued a statement on March 22, branding the current moves of the Japanese reactionaries to distort history as a dastardly artifice to cover up Japan's crime-woven past and evade its settlement and an intolerable criminal act prompted by the heinous intention to hasten its militarization and gratify their wild design to stage a comeback to Korea.
 Noting that their maneuvers to make distorted history textbooks getting more undisguised are an intensive expression and extension of their militarist ambition and reinvasion scheme which have reached a dangerous stage, the statement goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 History does not change, even if anyone distorts it, nor is erased, even if anyone covers it up. The tighter the Japanese reactionaries cling to the moves to distort history, the clearer their aggressive ambition stands out. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 However desperately they may try to distort history and cover up Japan's past crimes, they cannot conceal the past marred by crimes nor can they evade their obligation to redress it. Knowing this clearly, they should give up right away their reckless moves to make distorted history textbooks.
